# GitLab CI Guidance

## Project Context

- Workflow path: {{ workflow_path | default(".gitlab-ci.yml") }}
- Python versions: {{ python_versions | default("configured in CI") }}
- Package manager: {{ package_manager | default("detected by Akira") }}

## Pipeline Shape

- Structure `.gitlab-ci.yml` around `stages` and jobs; jobs in later stages
  implicitly wait for earlier stages unless `needs` changes the graph.
- Keep jobs focused: install, lint, type-check, test, build, and deploy should
  be easy to scan.
- Use `rules` for branch, tag, merge request, and file-change conditions;
  `only` and `except` are legacy and should not be added to new jobs.
- Use `needs` for DAG pipelines when a job can start before all jobs in the
  previous stage finish.

{% if package_manager | default("") == "uv" %}
## uv In CI

- Install uv before syncing dependencies.
- Cache uv-managed dependencies when the runner cache is already configured.
- Use locked installs for repeatable CI runs.
{% endif %}

## Artifacts And Caching

- Use `cache` for dependencies reused between pipeline runs, such as package
  manager caches.
- Use `artifacts` to pass files between jobs in the same pipeline, such as
  coverage reports, build outputs, or test logs.
- Set artifact expiration intentionally so large build outputs do not persist
  indefinitely.
- Keep cache keys tied to lock files when dependencies should refresh after
  lock changes.

## Containers And Runners

- Choose Docker-in-Docker only when the runner is configured for it and the
  security tradeoff is acceptable.
- Prefer socket binding only on runners where host Docker access is an explicit
  operational decision.
- Keep runner tags and image names stable so jobs land on expected executors.
- Separate container build jobs from test jobs unless they genuinely share the
  same image contract.

## Variables And Releases

- Use protected variables for values available only to protected branches or
  tags.
- Use masked variables for secrets that must never appear in job logs.
- Separate merge request validation from release and deployment jobs.
- Keep environment names and deployment URLs explicit for GitLab environments.

## Avoid

- Adding `only` or `except` to new jobs instead of `rules`.
- Using `cache` to pass build artifacts between jobs.
- Printing variables that may contain tokens or cloud credentials.
- Jobs that depend on implicit runner state outside the repository and CI
  variables.
